# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: messagepack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A **binary-to-text encoding** is a data encoding scheme that represents binary data as plain text.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Generally, the binary data consists of a sequence of arbitrary 8-bit byte (a.k.a. octet) values and the text is restricted to the printable character codes of commonly-used character encodings such as ASCII.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] In general, arbitrary binary data contains values that are not printable character codes, so software designed to only handle text fails to process such data.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Encoding binary data as text allows information that is not inherently stored as text to be processed by software that otherwise cannot process arbitrary binary data.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The software cannot interpret the information, but it can perform useful operations on the data such as transmit and store.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] PGP documentation (RFC 9580) uses the term "ASCII armor" for binary-to-text encoding when referring to Base64.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Conceptually, binary-to-text encoding differs from numeric representation for a numeric base (radix).
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] For example, decimal is a scheme for representing a value as base-10, but it is not a binary-to-text encoding.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A binary-to-text encoding could be devised that uses decimal representation for encoded data, but such a system would use only 10 values of a 4-bit encoded sequence, leaving 6 values unused.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A more efficient encoding would use all 16 values.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] This is Base16 which uses hexadecimal for encoding each 4-bit sequence.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Notably, because 16 is a power of two, Base16 and hexadecimal are indistinguishable in practice even though they differ conceptually.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Escape encodings such as percent-encoding and quoted-printable also allow for representing arbitrary binary data as text, but in a significantly different way.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A binary-to-text encoding involves encoding an entire input sequence whereas an escape encoding allows for embedding binary data in data that is already and inherently text.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A binary-to-text encoding enables transmitting data on a communication channel that does not allow arbitrary binary data (such as email or NNTP) or is not 8-bit clean.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The encoding enables transmitting binary data over a communications protocol that is designed to carry human-readable (i.e.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Often such a protocol only supports 7-bit character values (and within that avoids certain control codes), and may require line breaks at certain maximum intervals, and may not maintain whitespace.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Thus, only the 94 printable ASCII characters are safe to use to convey data.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The ASCII text-encoding standard uses 7 bits to encode characters.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] With this it is possible to encode 128 (i.e.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] 27) unique values (0–127) to represent the alphabetic, numeric, and punctuation characters commonly used in English, plus a selection of non-printable control characters.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] In contrast, most computers store data in memory organized in eight-bit bytes (a.k.a. octets).
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Files that contain machine-executable code and non-textual data typically contain all 256 possible eight-bit byte values.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Many computer programs came to rely on this distinction between seven-bit *text* and eight-bit *binary* data, and would not function properly if non-ASCII characters appeared in data that was expected to include only ASCII text.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] For example, if the value of the eighth bit is not preserved, the program might interpret a byte value above 127 as a flag telling it to perform some function.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] It is often desired to send non-textual data through a text-based system, such as attaching an image to an e-mail message.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] To accomplish this, the data is encoded in some way, such that 8-bit data is encoded as 7-bit ASCII characters (generally using only alphanumeric and punctuation characters—the ASCII printable characters).
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Upon arrival at its destination, it is then decoded back to its 8-bit form.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] This process is referred to as binary to text encoding.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Many programs perform this conversion to allow for data-transport, such as PGP and GNU Privacy Guard.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Binary-to-text encoding methods are also used as a mechanism for encoding plain text.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Some systems have a more limited character set they can handle; not only are they not 8-bit clean, some cannot even handle every printable ASCII character.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Other systems have limits on the number of characters that may appear between line breaks, such as the "1000 characters per line" limit of some Simple Mail Transfer Protocol software, as allowed by RFC 2821.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Still others add headers or trailers to the text.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A few poorly-regarded but still-used protocols use in-band signaling, causing confusion if specific patterns appear in the message.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The best-known is the string "From " (including trailing space) at the beginning of a line, used to separate mail messages in the mbox file format.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] By using a binary-to-text encoding on messages that are already plain text, then decoding on the other end, one can make such systems appear to be completely transparent.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] This is sometimes referred to as 'ASCII armoring'.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] For example, the ViewState component of ASP.NET uses base64 encoding to safely transmit text via HTTP POST, in order to avoid delimiter collision.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The table below describes notable binary-to-text encodings.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The efficiency listed is the ratio between the number of bits in the input and the number of bits in the encoded output.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] For any encoding that maps *n* input possibilities into one 8-bit character, the efficiency is log2(*n*)/8.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Some older and today uncommon formats include BOO (a base64), BTOA (vaguely-defined "binary to ascii", historically base85, today in JavaScript base64), and USR encoding.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Base64 (with many variants including uuencoding) maps sequences of 6 bits to printable characters.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Since there are more than 26 = 64 printable characters, this is possible.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] A given sequence of bytes is translated by viewing it as a stream of bits, breaking this stream into chunks of 6 bits and generating the sequence of corresponding characters.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] The different encodings differ in the mapping between sequences of bits and characters and in how the resulting text is formatted.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Some encodings (the original version of BinHex and the recommended encoding for CipherSaber) use four bits instead of six, mapping all possible sequences of 4 bits onto the 16 standard hexadecimal digits.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] Using 4 bits per encoded character leads to a 50% longer output than base64, but simplifies encoding and decoding—expanding each byte in the source independently to two encoded bytes is simpler than base64's expanding 3 source bytes to 4 encoded bytes.
[src:messagepack/binary-to-text-encoding] This theoretically permits encodings, such as base128, between PETSCII-speaking machines.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] This is a **comparison of data serialization formats**, various ways to convert complex objects to sequences of bits.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] It does not include markup languages used exclusively as document file formats.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The "classic" format is plain text, and an XML format is also supported.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Theoretically possible due to abstraction, but no implementation is included.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but text and JSON formats are available.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Means that generic tools/libraries know how to encode, decode, and dereference a reference to another piece of data in the same document.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] A tool may require the IDL file, but no more.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Excludes custom, non-standardized referencing techniques.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**ASN.1 has X.681 (Information Object System), X.682 (Constraints), and X.683 (Parameterization) that allow for the precise specification of open types where the types of values can be identified by integers, by OIDs, etc.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] OIDs are a standard format for globally unique identifiers, as well as a standard notation ("absolute reference") for referencing a component of a value.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] For example, PKIX uses such notation in RFC 5912.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] With such notation (constraints on parameterized types using information object sets), generic ASN.1 tools/libraries can automatically encode/decode/resolve references within a document.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, a json encoder is available.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but a text format is available.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The RFC CSV specification only deals with delimiters, newlines, and quote characters; it does not directly deal with serializing programming data structures.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The netstrings specification only deals with nested byte strings; anything else is outside the scope of the specification.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**PHP will unserialize any floating-point number correctly, but will serialize them to their full decimal expansion.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**XML data bindings and SOAP serialization tools provide type-safe XML serialization of programming data structures into XML.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Shown are XML values that can be placed in XML elements and attributes.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**This syntax is not compatible with the Internet-Draft, but is used by some dialects of Lisp.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] All basic Ion types have a null variant, as its 0xXf tag.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Any tag beginning with 0x0X other than 0x0f defines ignored padding.
[src:messagepack/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Interpretation of Netstrings is entirely application- or schema-dependent.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Data exchange is similar to data integration except that data may be restructured with possible loss of content.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] There may be no way to transform a particular collection based on exchange constraints.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Conversely, there may be multiple ways to transform the data, in which case one option must be identified in order to achieve compatibility between source and target.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] There are two main types of data exchange: broadcast and peer-to-peer (a.k.a. unicast).
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] For broadcast, data is transmitted simultaneously to all consumers.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Just as a conference call, all participants get the same information from the speaker at the same time.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] For peer-to-peer, data is sent to a single receiver, defined by a specific address.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] For example, a letter goes to just one mail box.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] In some domains, a multiple source and target schema (proprietary data formats) may exist.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] An exchange or interchange format is often developed for a single domain, and then necessary routines (mappings) are written to (indirectly) transform/translate each and every source schema to each and every target schema by using the interchange format as an intermediate step.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] That requires less work than writing and debugging the many routines that would be required to directly translate each source schema directly to each target schema.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] A data exchange (a.k.a. interchange) language defines a domain-independent way to represent data.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] These languages have evolved from being markup and display-oriented to support the encoding of metadata that describes the structural attributes of the information.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Practice has shown that certain types of formal languages are better suited for this task than others, since their specification is driven by a formal process instead of particular software implementation.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] For example, XML is a markup language that was designed to enable the creation of dialects (the definition of domain-specific sublanguages).
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] However, it does not contain domain-specific dictionaries or fact types.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Beneficial to a reliable data exchange is the availability of standard dictionaries-taxonomies and tools libraries such as parsers, schema validators, and transformation tools.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] The popularity of XML for data exchange on the World Wide Web has several reasons.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] First of all, it is closely related to the preexisting standards Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), and as such a parser written to support these two languages can be easily extended to support XML as well.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] For example, XHTML has been defined as a format that is formal XML, but understood correctly by most (if not all) HTML parsers.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] YAML was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor with notion similar to reStructuredText and wiki syntax.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] YAML 1.2 also includes a shorthand notion that is compatible with JSON, and as such any JSON document is also valid YAML; this however does not hold the other way.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] REBOL was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] It uses a simple free-form syntax with minimal punctuation and a rich set of data types (such as URL, email, date and time, tuple, string, tag) that respect common standards.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] It is designed to not need any additional meta-language, being designed in a metacircular fashion which is why the parse dialect used for definitions and transformations of REBOL dialects is also itself a dialect of REBOL.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] REBOL was used as a source of inspiration for JSON.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] The dictionary also includes standardized fact types.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] The terms and relation types together can be used to create and interpret expressions of facts, knowledge, requirements and other information.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] Gellish can be used in combination with SQL, RDF/XML, OWL and various other meta-languages.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] The Gellish standard is a combination of ISO 10303-221 (AP221) and ISO 15926.
[src:messagepack/data-exchange] The following describes and compares popular data exchange languages.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In computing, **endianness** is the order in which bytes within a *word* data type are transmitted over a data communication medium or addressed in computer memory, counting only byte significance compared to earliness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (**BE**) or **little-endian** (**LE**).
[src:messagepack/endianness] Computers store information in various-sized groups of binary bits.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Each group is assigned a number, called its *address*, that the computer uses to access that data.
[src:messagepack/endianness] On most modern computers, the smallest data group with an address is eight bits long, and is called a *byte*.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Larger groups comprise two or more bytes; for example, a *word* often contains 32 bits or 64 bits.
[src:messagepack/endianness] There are two principal ways a computer could number the individual bytes in a larger group, starting at either end.
[src:messagepack/endianness] A big-endian system stores the most significant byte of a word at the smallest memory address and the least significant byte at the largest.
[src:messagepack/endianness] A little-endian system, in contrast, stores the least-significant byte at the smallest address.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Of the two, big-endian is thus closer to the way the digits of numbers are written left-to-right in English, with the most significant digit first, comparing digits to bytes and assuming addresses increase from left to right.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Both types of endianness are in widespread use in digital electronic engineering.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The initial choice of endianness of a new design is often arbitrary, but later technology revisions and updates perpetuate the existing endianness to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Big-endianness is the dominant ordering in networking protocols, such as in the Internet protocol suite, where it is referred to as *network order*, transmitting the most significant byte first.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Conversely, little-endianness is the dominant ordering for processor architectures (x86, most ARM implementations, base RISC-V implementations) and their associated memory.
[src:messagepack/endianness] File formats can use either ordering; some formats use a mixture of both or contain an indicator of which ordering is used throughout the file.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Endianness is primarily expressed as **big-endian** (BE) or **little-endian** (LE), terms introduced by Danny Cohen in an Internet Experiment Note published in 1980.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Cohen borrowed the terms from an absurd episode in the satirical novel *Gulliver's Travels* by Jonathan Swift.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In the imaginary land of Lilliput, scholars are fiercely divided by a never-ending debate over how correctly to break the shell of a boiled egg.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Those who insist on breaking the big end of the shell are Big-Endians, while their opponents who break the opposite end of the shell are Little-Endians.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Computer memory consists of a sequence of storage cells (smallest addressable units); in machines that support byte addressing, those units are called *bytes*.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Each byte is identified and accessed in hardware and software by its memory address.
[src:messagepack/endianness] If the total number of bytes in memory is *n*, then addresses are enumerated from 0 to *n* − 1.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Computer programs often use data structures or fields that may consist of more data than can be stored in one byte.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In the context of this article, where its type cannot be arbitrarily complicated, a *field* consists of a consecutive sequence of bytes and represents a *simple data value* which, at least potentially, can be manipulated by *one* single hardware instruction.
[src:messagepack/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte simple data value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:messagepack/endianness] There are exceptions to this rule – for example, the Add instruction of the IBM 1401 addresses variable-length fields at their low-order (highest-addressed) position with their lengths being defined by a word mark set at their high-order (lowest-addressed) position.
[src:messagepack/endianness] When an operation such as addition is performed, the processor begins at the low-order positions at the high addresses of the two fields and works its way down to the high-order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Another important attribute of a byte being part of a *field* is its *significance*.
[src:messagepack/endianness] These attributes of the parts of a field play an important role in the sequence the bytes are accessed by the computer hardware, more precisely: by the low-level algorithms contributing to the results of a computer instruction.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Positional number systems (mostly base 2, or less often base 10) are the predominant way of representing and particularly of manipulating integer data by computers.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In pure form, this is valid for moderately sized non-negative integers, e.g., of C data type `unsigned`.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In such a number system, the *value* of a digit that contributes to the whole number is determined not only by its value as a single digit, but also by the position it holds in the complete number, called its significance.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In *big-endian* and *little-endian*, the *end* is the extremity where the *big* or *little* significance is written in the location indexed by the lowest memory address.
[src:messagepack/endianness] When character (text) strings are to be compared with one another, e.g., in order to support some mechanism like sorting, this is very frequently done lexicographically where a single positional element (character) also has a positional value.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Lexicographical comparison means almost everywhere: first character ranks highest, as in the telephone book.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Almost all machines that can do this using a single instruction are big-endian or at least mixed-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Integer numbers written as text are always represented most significant digit first in memory, which is similar to big-endian, independently of text direction.
[src:messagepack/endianness] When memory bytes are printed sequentially from left to right (e.g., in a hex dump), little-endian representation of integers has the significance decreasing from right to left.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In other words, it appears backwards when visualized, which can be counterintuitive.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This behavior arises, for example, in FourCC or similar techniques that involve packing characters into an integer, so that it becomes a sequence of specific characters in memory.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For example, take the string "JOHN", stored in hexadecimal ASCII.
[src:messagepack/endianness] On big-endian machines, the value appears left-to-right, coinciding with the correct string order for reading the result ("J O H N").
[src:messagepack/endianness] But on a little-endian machine, one would see "N H O J".
[src:messagepack/endianness] Middle-endian machines complicate this even further; for example, on the PDP-11, a 32-bit float is stored as two 16-bit words "JO" "HN" in big-endian, with the characters in the 16-bit words being stored in little-endian, resulting in "O J N H".
[src:messagepack/endianness] Byte-swapping consists of rearranging bytes to change endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Many compilers provide built-ins that are likely to be compiled into native processor instructions (`bswap`/`movbe`), such as `__builtin_bswap32`.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some CPU instruction sets provide native support for endian byte swapping, such as `bswap` (x86 — 486 and later, i960 — i960Jx and later), and `rev` (ARMv6 and later).
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some compilers have built-in facilities for byte swapping.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For example, GNU Fortran and the Intel Fortran Compiler both support the non-standard `CONVERT` specifier when opening a file, e.g.: `OPEN(unit, CONVERT='BIG_ENDIAN',...)`.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Other compilers have options for generating code that globally enables the conversion for all file IO operations.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This permits the reuse of code on a system with the opposite endianness without code modification.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For example, a 32-bit memory location with content `4A 00 00 00` can be read at the same address as either 8-bit (value = 4A), 16-bit (004A), 24-bit (00004A), or 32-bit (0000004A), all of which retain the same numeric value.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Although this little-endian property is rarely used directly by high-level programmers, it is occasionally employed by code optimizers as well as by assembly language programmers.
[src:messagepack/endianness] While not allowed by C++, such type punning code is allowed as "implementation-defined" by the C11 standard and commonly used in code interacting with hardware.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some operations in positional number systems have a natural or preferred order in which the elementary steps are to be executed.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This order may affect their performance on small-scale byte-addressable processors and microcontrollers.
[src:messagepack/endianness] However, high-performance processors usually fetch multi-byte operands from memory in the same amount of time they would have fetched a single byte, so the complexity of the hardware is not affected by the byte ordering.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Addition, subtraction, and multiplication start at the least significant digit position and propagate the carry to the subsequent more significant position.
[src:messagepack/endianness] On most systems, the address of a multi-byte value is the address of its first byte (the byte with the lowest address).
[src:messagepack/endianness] The implementation of these operations is marginally simpler using little-endian machines, where this first byte contains the least significant digit.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Comparison and division start at the most significant digit and propagate a possible carry to the subsequent less significant digits.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For fixed-length numerical values (typically of length 1,2,4,8,16), the implementation of these operations is marginally simpler on big-endian machines.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some big-endian processors (e.g., the IBM System/360 and its successors) contain hardware instructions for lexicographically comparing varying-length character strings.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The normal data transport by an assignment statement is, in principle, independent of the endianness of the processor.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Many historical and extant processors use a big-endian memory representation, either exclusively or as a design option.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The IBM System/360 uses big-endian byte order, as do its successors System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The PDP-10 uses big-endian addressing for byte-oriented instructions.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The IBM Series/1 minicomputer uses big-endian byte order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The Motorola 6800 / 6801, the 6809 and the 68000 series of processors use the big-endian format.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Solely big-endian architectures include the IBM z/Architecture and OpenRISC.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The PDP-11 minicomputer, however, uses little-endian byte order, as does its VAX successor.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The Datapoint 2200 used simple bit-serial logic with little-endian to facilitate carry propagation.
[src:messagepack/endianness] When Intel developed the 8008 microprocessor for Datapoint, they used little-endian for compatibility.
[src:messagepack/endianness] However, as Intel was unable to deliver the 8008 in time, Datapoint used a medium-scale integration equivalent, but the little-endianness was retained in most Intel designs, including the MCS-48 and the 8086 and its x86 successors, including IA-32 and x86-64 processors.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The MOS Technology 6502 family (including Western Design Center 65802 and 65C816), the Zilog Z80 (including Z180 and eZ80), the Altera Nios II, the Atmel AVR, the Andes Technology NDS32, the Qualcomm Hexagon, and many other processors and processor families are also little-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The Intel 8051, unlike other Intel processors, expects 16-bit addresses for LJMP and LCALL in big-endian format; however, xCALL instructions store the return address onto the stack in little-endian format.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some instruction set architectures feature a setting which allows for switchable endianness in data fetches and stores, instruction fetches, or both; those instruction set architectures are referred to as *bi-endian*.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Architectures that support switchable endianness include PowerPC/Power ISA, SPARC V9, ARM versions 3 and above, DEC Alpha, MIPS, Intel i860, PA-RISC, SuperH SH-4, IA-64, C-Sky, and RISC-V.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This feature can improve performance or simplify the logic of networking devices and software.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The word *bi-endian*, when said of hardware, denotes the capability of the machine to compute or pass data in either endian format.
[src:messagepack/endianness] IBM AIX and IBM i run in big-endian mode on bi-endian Power ISA; Linux originally ran in big-endian mode, but by 2019, IBM had transitioned to little-endian mode for Linux to ease the porting of Linux software from x86 to Power.
[src:messagepack/endianness] SPARC has no relevant little-endian deployment, as both Oracle Solaris and Linux run in big-endian mode on bi-endian SPARC systems, and can be considered big-endian in practice.
[src:messagepack/endianness] ARM, C-Sky, and RISC-V have no relevant big-endian deployments and can be considered little-endian in practice.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The term *bi-endian* refers primarily to how a processor treats data accesses.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Instruction accesses (fetches of instruction words) on a given processor may still assume a fixed endianness, even if data accesses are fully bi-endian, though this is not always the case, such as on Intel's IA-64-based Itanium CPU, which allows both.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some nominally bi-endian CPUs require motherboard help to fully switch endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In the absence of this unusual motherboard hardware, device driver software must write to different addresses to undo the incomplete transformation and also must perform a normal byte swap.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Some CPUs, such as many PowerPC processors intended for embedded use and almost all SPARC processors, allow per-page choice of endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] SPARC processors since the late 1990s (SPARC v9 compliant processors) allow data endianness to be chosen with each individual instruction that loads from or stores to memory.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The ARM architecture supports two big-endian modes, called *BE-8* and *BE-32*.
[src:messagepack/endianness] CPUs up to ARMv5 only support BE-32 or word-invariant mode.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Here, any naturally aligned 32-bit access works like in little-endian mode, but access to a byte or 16-bit word is redirected to the corresponding address and unaligned access is not allowed.
[src:messagepack/endianness] ARMv6 introduces BE-8 or byte-invariant mode, where access to a single byte works as in little-endian mode, but accessing a 16-bit, 32-bit or (starting with ARMv8) 64-bit word results in a byte swap of the data.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This simplifies unaligned memory access as well as memory-mapped access to registers other than 32-bit.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Many processors have instructions to convert a word in a register to the opposite endianness, that is, they swap the order of the bytes in a 16-, 32- or 64-bit word.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Recent Intel x86 and x86-64 architecture CPUs have a MOVBE instruction (Intel Core since generation 4, after Atom), which fetches a big-endian format word from memory or writes a word into memory in big-endian format.
[src:messagepack/endianness] These processors are otherwise thoroughly little-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] There are also devices that use different formats in different places.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For instance, the BQ27421 Texas Instruments battery gauge uses the little-endian format for its registers and the big-endian format for its random-access memory.
[src:messagepack/endianness] SPARC historically used big-endian until version 9, which is bi-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Similarly, early IBM POWER processors were big-endian, but the PowerPC and Power ISA descendants are now bi-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The ARM architecture was little-endian before version 3, when it became bi-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Although many processors use little-endian storage for all types of data (integer, floating point), there are a number of hardware architectures where floating-point numbers are represented in big-endian form while integers are represented in little-endian form.
[src:messagepack/endianness] There are ARM processors that have mixed-endian floating-point representation for double-precision numbers: each of the two 32-bit words is stored as little-endian, but the most significant word is stored first.
[src:messagepack/endianness] VAX floating point stores little-endian 16-bit words in big-endian order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Because there have been many floating-point formats with no network standard representation for them, the XDR standard uses big-endian IEEE 754 as its representation.
[src:messagepack/endianness] It may therefore appear strange that the widespread IEEE 754 floating-point standard does not specify endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Theoretically, this means that even standard IEEE floating-point data written by one machine might not be readable by another.
[src:messagepack/endianness] However, on modern standard computers (i.e., implementing IEEE 754), one may safely assume that the endianness is the same for floating-point numbers as for integers, making the conversion straightforward regardless of data type.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Small embedded systems using special floating-point formats may be another matter, however.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Most instructions considered so far contain the size (lengths) of their operands within the operation code.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Frequently available operand lengths are 1, 2, 4, 8, or 16 bytes.
[src:messagepack/endianness] But there are also architectures where the length of an operand may be held in a separate field of the instruction or with the operand itself, e.g., by means of a word mark.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Such an approach allows operand lengths up to 256 bytes or larger.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The data types of such operands are character strings or BCD.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Machines able to manipulate such data with one instruction (e.g. compare, add) include the IBM 1401, 1410, 1620, System/360, System/370, ESA/390, and z/Architecture, all of them of type big-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Numerous other orderings, generically called *middle-endian* or *mixed-endian*, are possible.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The PDP-11 is primarily a 16-bit little-endian system.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The instructions to convert between floating-point and integer values in the optional floating-point processor of the PDP-11/45, PDP-11/70, and in some later processors, stored 32-bit *double precision integer long* values with the 16-bit halves swapped from the expected little-endian order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The UNIX C compiler used the same format for 32-bit long integers.
[src:messagepack/endianness] UNIX was one of the first systems to allow the same code to be compiled for platforms with different internal representations.
[src:messagepack/endianness] One of the first programs converted was supposed to print out `Unix`, but on the Series/1 it printed `nUxi` instead.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Segment descriptors of IA-32 and compatible processors keep a 32-bit base address of the segment stored in little-endian order, but in four nonconsecutive bytes, at relative positions 2, 3, 4 and 7 of the descriptor start.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Hardware description languages (HDLs) used to express digital logic often support arbitrary endianness, with arbitrary granularity.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For example, in SystemVerilog, a word can be defined as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The recognition of endianness is important when reading a file or filesystem created on a computer with different endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] An attempt to read such a file using Fortran on a system of the other endianness results in a run-time error, because the count fields are incorrect.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Unicode text can optionally start with a byte order mark (BOM) to signal the endianness of the file or stream.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In UTF-32 for example, a big-endian file should start with `00 00 FE FF`; a little-endian should start with `FF FE 00 00`.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Application binary data formats, such as MATLAB *.mat* files, or the *.bil* data format, used in topography, are usually endianness-independent.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This is achieved by storing the data always in one fixed endianness or carrying with the data a switch to indicate the endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] An example of the former is the binary XLS file format that is portable between Windows and Mac systems and always little-endian, requiring the Mac application to swap the bytes on load and save when running on a big-endian Motorola 68K or PowerPC processor.
[src:messagepack/endianness] TIFF image files are an example of the second strategy, whose header instructs the application about the endianness of their internal binary integers.
[src:messagepack/endianness] If a file starts with the signature `MM` it means that integers are represented as big-endian, while `II` means little-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Those signatures need a single 16-bit word each, and they are palindromes, so they are endianness independent.
[src:messagepack/endianness] `I` stands for Intel and `M` stands for Motorola.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Intel CPUs are little-endian, while Motorola 680x0 CPUs are big-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] This explicit signature allows a TIFF reader program to swap bytes if necessary when a given file was generated by a TIFF writer program running on a computer with a different endianness.
[src:messagepack/endianness] ZFS, which combines a filesystem and a logical volume manager, is known to provide adaptive endianness and to work with both big-endian and little-endian systems.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Many IETF RFCs use the term *network order*, meaning the order of transmission for bytes *over the wire* in network protocols.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Among others, the historic RFC 1700 defines the network order for protocols in the Internet protocol suite to be big-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] However, not all protocols use big-endian byte order as the network order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol uses little-endian byte order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] In CANopen, multi-byte parameters are always sent least significant byte first (little-endian).
[src:messagepack/endianness] The same is true for Ethernet Powerlink.
[src:messagepack/endianness] These functions may be a no-op on a big-endian system.
[src:messagepack/endianness] While the high-level network protocols usually consider the byte (mostly meant as *octet*) as their atomic unit, the lowest layers of a network stack may deal with the ordering of bits within a byte.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Bit ordering is sometimes referred to as little-endian or big-endian.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Bit ordering does not need to be the same as byte ordering.
[src:messagepack/endianness] For example, RS-232 transmits bits least significant first, I2C transmits bits most significant first, and SPI can be sent in either order.
[src:messagepack/endianness] Ethernet transmits individual bits least significant first, but bytes are sent big-endian.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] Data structures processed by MessagePack loosely correspond to those used in JSON format.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] MessagePack is more compact than JSON, but imposes limitations on array and integer sizes.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] On the other hand, it allows binary data and non-UTF-8 strings.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] In JSON, map keys have to be strings, but MessagePack has no such limitation, and any type can be a map key, including types like maps and arrays, and, like YAML, numbers.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] Compared to BSON, MessagePack is more space-efficient.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] BSON is designed for fast in-memory manipulation, whereas MessagePack is designed for efficient transmission over the wire.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] For example, BSON requires null terminators at the end of all strings and inserts string indexes for list elements, while MessagePack does not.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] BSON represents both arrays and maps internally as documents, which are maps, where an array is a map with keys as decimal strings counting up from 0.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] MessagePack on the other hand represents both maps and arrays as arrays, where each map key–value pair is contiguous, making odd items keys and even items values.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] The Protocol Buffers format provides a significantly more compact transmission format than MessagePack because it does not transmit field names.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] However, while JSON and MessagePack aim to serialize arbitrary data structures with type tags, Protocol Buffers requires a schema to define the data types.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] Protocol Buffers compiler creates boilerplate code in the target language to facilitate integration of serialization into the application code; MessagePack returns only a dynamically typed data structure and provides no automatic structure checks.
[src:messagepack/messagepack] MessagePack is referenced in RFC 7049 of CBOR.
[src:messagepack/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:messagepack/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:messagepack/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:messagepack/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:messagepack/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:messagepack/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:messagepack/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:messagepack/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:messagepack/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:messagepack/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:messagepack/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:messagepack/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:messagepack/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:messagepack/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:messagepack/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:messagepack/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:messagepack/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:messagepack/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:messagepack/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:messagepack/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:messagepack/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:messagepack/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:messagepack/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:messagepack/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:messagepack/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:messagepack/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:messagepack/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:messagepack/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:messagepack/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:messagepack/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:messagepack/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:messagepack/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:messagepack/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:messagepack/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:messagepack/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:messagepack/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:messagepack/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:messagepack/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:messagepack/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:messagepack/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:messagepack/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:messagepack/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:messagepack/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:messagepack/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:messagepack/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:messagepack/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:messagepack/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:messagepack/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:messagepack/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:messagepack/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:messagepack/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:messagepack/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:messagepack/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:messagepack/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:messagepack/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:messagepack/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:messagepack/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:messagepack/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:messagepack/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
